  "query": "How does the evidence for using acoustically reflective materials on fishing gear compare to attaching acoustically reflective objects for reducing marine mammal entanglement?",
  "relevant_summary": "The evidence for using acoustically reflective materials on fishing gear shows mixed results from five studies across multiple locations. Two of three controlled studies in the North Sea, Bay of Fundy, and South Atlantic Ocean found that fishing nets made from acoustically reflective materials (iron-oxide or barium sulfate) had fewer entanglements of harbour porpoises than conventional fishing nets, while one study found that nets made from barium sulfate did not reduce dolphin entanglements (Action 2807). Additionally, two behavioural studies examined echolocation responses, with one finding that harbour porpoises used fewer echolocation clicks at barium sulfate nets, while another found similar echolocation activity at both net types (Action 2807). In contrast, the evidence for attaching acoustically reflective objects to fishing gear is more limited and shows no effectiveness. Only two studies evaluated this approach, with one controlled study in the Timor Sea and Arafura Sea finding that attaching metallic bead chains to fishing nets did not reduce dolphin entanglements, and another study in the Gulf of Alaska finding that attaching acrylic beads next to fishing hooks did not reduce predation on fish catches by sperm whales (Action 2806). The evidence suggests that incorporating acoustically reflective materials into the gear itself may be more promising than attaching separate reflective objects, though results remain inconsistent across species and locations.",
